def detect_types(data):
    numerical_preds=[]
    categorical_preds=[]
     
    
    for i in list(data):
        if(data[i].dtype=='object'):
            categorical_preds.append(i)
        else:
            numerical_preds.append(i)
    
    return numerical_preds,categorical_preds


def comp_auc(target, predictions):
    return roc_auc_score(target, predictions)


def graph_exploration_cat(feature_binned,target):
  
    '''
    if(sum(feature_binned.isnull())>0):
        feature_binned=feature_binned.cat.add_categories('NA').fillna('NA')
    '''
    
    result = ks.concat([feature_binned, target], axis=1)
    tg_mn=target.mean()
    
    gb=result.groupby(feature_binned)
    counts = gb.size().to_frame(name='counts')
    final=counts.join(gb.agg({result.columns[1]: 'mean'}).rename(columns={result.columns[1]: 'target_mean'})).reset_index()

    final=final.to_pandas() 
    # We are fine to use pandas here, because 'final' table will be always small with some aggregations only
    final['odds_ratio']=np.log2((final['counts']*final['target_mean']+100*tg_mn)/((100+final['counts'])*tg_mn))  
        
    
    sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(15,10)})
    fig, ax =plt.subplots(2,1)
    sns.barplot(x=final.columns[0],y='counts',data=final,color="blue",ax=ax[0])
    ax[0].xaxis.set_visible(False)
    sns.barplot(x=final.columns[0],y='odds_ratio',data=final,color="green",ax=ax[1])
    plt.xticks(rotation=35)
    plt.show()
    
def graph_exploration_num(feature_binned,target):
  
    if(sum(feature_binned.isnull())>0):
        feature_binned=feature_binned.cat.add_categories('NA').fillna('NA')
    
    result = pd.concat([feature_binned, target], axis=1)
    
    gb=result.groupby(feature_binned)
    counts = gb.size().to_frame(name='counts')
    final=counts.join(gb.agg({result.columns[1]: 'mean'}).rename(columns={result.columns[1]: 'target_mean'})).reset_index()
    final['odds_ratio']=np.log2((final['counts']*final['target_mean']+100*np.mean(target))/((100+final['counts'])*np.mean(target)))
        
    sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(15,10)})
    fig, ax =plt.subplots(2,1)
    sns.countplot(x=feature_binned, hue=target, data=result,ax=ax[0])
    sns.barplot(x=final.columns[0],y='odds_ratio',data=final,color="green",ax=ax[1])
    plt.show()
    
def replace_categories(data, categorical_preds, num_categories):   
    for i in categorical_preds:
        if data[i].nunique()>num_categories:
            print(i)
            print(data[i].nunique())
            top_n_cat=data[i].value_counts()[:num_categories].to_pandas().index.tolist()
            
            
            def f(row):
                if row in top_n_cat:
                    val = row
                else:
                    val = 'other'
                return val
            

            data[i]=data[i].apply(f)
            
            #data[i]=data[i].apply(lambda x: data[i] if x in top_n_cat  else 'other')
            
            #data[i]=np.where(data[i].isin(top_n_cat),data[i],'other')   
    return data

Explanatory data analysis of categorical variables¶

Odds_ratio means log2 of ratio of target rate within given category and total target rate of dataset. For Example, when target rate in dataset is 0.05 and target rate within particular category is 0.1, than odds_ratio = log2(0.1/0.05)=1.

Observations from EDA of categorical variables¶

  • Powerfull predictors seems to be Sex, where men are much more likely to have higher salary than women.

  • Education looks also as the strong predictor, where 'bachelor' (university degrees) and 'other' categorie seems to have higher salary. On the other hand 'children' category is widely populated with very low target rate.

  • Major industry code seems to be also Major industry code where 'Not in universe' seems to be highly agains the target.

Useless predictors seems to be: unemp_reason, region_prev_res, mig_chg_reg, citizenship, mig_prev_sunbelt, mig_chg_msa, mig_same, mig_move_reg, union_member, vet_question, hisp_origin

Explanatory data analysis of numerical variables¶

So far we were not limited for using pandas functions at all. For the EDA of categorical will use .to_pandas() function to iteratively 2 columns - target and variable that is being explored. If in some cases this would not be suitable solution because of lack of memory I would try to solve this by sampling of the rows. From the same reason, I used auc metric from sci-kit learn.

In [76]:
for i in numerical_preds:
    print(i)
    data=data_ks[[i,'target']].to_pandas()
    
    print('SAME FREQUENCY BINNING:')
    
    borders=[]
    for j in [15,30,45,60,75,90]:
        borders=np.append(borders,np.nanpercentile(data[i],j))
    borders=np.concatenate(([data[i].min()-0.01], borders))
    borders=np.append(borders,data[i].max()+0.01)
    borders=list(dict.fromkeys(borders))
    graph_exploration_num(pd.cut(data[i],borders),data['target'])
    
    
    print('AUC of this variable:')
    auc=comp_auc(data['target'], data[i])
    if auc > 0.5:
        print(round(auc,3))
    else:
        print(round(1-auc,3))
    
    
    print('---------------------------------------------------------') 
    print('---------------------------------------------------------')

Preparing pyspark dataframe formodelling. The stepst are as following¶

  1. Convert categorical variables to one-hot encoding
  2. Join them with numerical variables to one columns together
  3. Common column called features is suitable source for pyspark ml library
In [120]:
from pyspark.ml.feature import OneHotEncoder, StringIndexer, VectorAssembler

stages = []
for categoricalCol in categorical_preds:
    stringIndexer = StringIndexer(inputCol = categoricalCol, outputCol = categoricalCol + 'Index')
    encoder = OneHotEncoder(inputCols=[stringIndexer.getOutputCol()], outputCols=[categoricalCol + "classVec"])
    stages += [stringIndexer, encoder]
label_stringIdx = StringIndexer(inputCol = 'target', outputCol = 'label')
stages += [label_stringIdx]
assemblerInputs = [c + "classVec" for c in categorical_preds] + numerical_preds
assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=assemblerInputs, outputCol="features")
stages += [assembler]

ml pipeline fulfills previous preparations

Fitting of random forest with spark ML library¶

Random forest is ensemble of independently constructed decision trees. Final prediction is consequently made as average from particular trees. Fitting of decision trees requires less data preparation than for example logistic regression, where linear relationship between target and variables is demanded. For example Therefore I do not need to care much about data preprocessing right now (i am not saying, that is never necessary). Next big advantage of decion trees is that in a similar way as nonlinearity implicitely finds interactions between variables. In the linear models you will never find interactions, unless you will create them manually.

Further steps¶

Those steps would in my opinion lead to icrease of the model performance.

  1. Focus on optimization of hyperparameters. Random forest have large hyperparameter that have impact to the model performance - subsample of row, subsample of columns, number of trees, maximal depth of the trees, minimal number of observations in each node, etc. Optimization of these could improve the performance.

  2. Try to use different algorithm - gradient boosting model would probably bring higher performance.

  3. Try some feature engineering and data preprocessing. There is lot of features that can be derived from given features. For example if the father and mother have the same country of origin, etc. Testing of new features into the model can bring additional performance.
